10.10 Particle Labeling¶

The goal of this notebook is to develop a python class for the purpose of counting and labeling flourescent particles captured in images from a prototype for a low-cost medical diagnostic device.

Observations:

  • The flourescence signal is largelyl confined to the green channel

10.10.1.3 Channels and Histograms¶

In [6]:
def histogram(c, bp=3, wp=252):
    """Return histogram and bins for a single channel."""
    hist = cv.calcHist([c], [0], None, [wp-bp+1], [bp, wp])
    bins = [b for b in range(bp, wp+1)]
    return hist, bins

def display_channel(c):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15, 5))
    ax[0].imshow(c.astype(np.uint8), cmap="gray")
    hist, bins = histogram(c.astype(np.uint8))
    ax[1].plot(bins, hist)

hist = [histogram(c) for c in split(img)]

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15, 5))
ax[0].imshow(img)
for i,c in enumerate(['r','g','b']):
    ax[1].plot(hist[i][1], hist[i][0], c=c, label=c)
ax[1].legend()

r, g, b = cv.split(img)
display_channel(r)
display_channel(g)
display_channel(b)

10.10.1.4 Cross-Channel Interference¶

What we see above is that the blue leds used to excite the flourophores have a large enough spectrum to bleed over into the green channel. It would be best if this could be corrected in the experiment, perhaps by positioning a bandpass filter in front of the leds.

What we will attempt here is subtract a multiple of blue channel from the green channel, followed by exposure adjustments. The goal is to provide a cleaner image for doing particle labeling and counting.

By trial and error, we find a weighted difference of the green and blue channels, and a rescaling of the tone curve that retains the particles and reduces background interference.

In [7]:
# subtract blue channel from green channel
pimg = (g - 0.53*b)
display_channel(pimg)

# set zero threshold
pimg = np.where(pimg < 0, 0, pimg).astype(np.uint8)
display_channel(pimg)

10.10.2.1 Finding and Displaying Particles¶

In [13]:
# find the objects and place bounding boxes

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15, 5))
slices = ndimage.find_objects(label_img)
sizes = [np.sqrt((b.stop-b.start)**2 + (a.stop-a.start)**2) for a,b in slices]
ax[1].hist(sizes, bins=200)
ax[1].set_xlim(0, 200)
ax[0].imshow(img)
for k,size in enumerate(sizes):
    if size > 50 and size < 200:
        a,b = slices[k]
        ya = a.start
        yb = a.stop
        xa = b.start
        xb = b.stop
        ax[0].plot([xa, xb, xb, xa, xa], [yb, yb, ya, ya, yb], 'w')
